<p>
Also remember that properly-done tests have a control group that gets no treatment.
(A treatment program must produce better results than the control group for it to claim
success.)
That is, in a test of A.A. treatment, you have two groups &#8212;
an A.A.-treated group, and a similar group that gets no treatment at all.
Assignment of people to the groups must be random &#8212; no cherry-picking is allowed.
Both groups may (and often do) contain
people who don't want to quit drinking, so it's a fair test.
<p>
